{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5106","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">In Spoken Tibetan, compound verbs are more common than simple verbs (verbs comprising only one syllable). For the most part, compound verbs consist of a noun and a “verbalizer.” Verbalizers (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱ་ཚིག་སྟོང་པ་</span>) are verbs that do not convey a specific meaning, or else mean “to do” in a general sense. Compound verbs of this sort generally comprise two or three syllables, but some contain up to five.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The three basic verbalizers are:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་</span> / <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གནང་</span> (H) “To do,” “to act” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་</span> / <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྐྱོན་</span> (H) “To make”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་</span> / <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་གནང་</span> (H) “To send,” “to do”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Other verbalizers (some of them used only rarely) include:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཟོ་</span> “To make” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་</span> (H) “To say,” “to take” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཞེས་</span> “To take” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསླངས་</span> “To lift” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལང་</span> “To get up” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འགྲོ་</span> “To go” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཤོར་</span> “To let go” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐེབས་</span> “To be caught,” “to be hit” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འཁོར་</span> “To circulate”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The choice of verbalizer is determined partly by whether the verb is volitional or non-volitional. The verbalizers <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཤོར་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འགྲོ་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལང་</span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐེབས་</span> are used in the formation of non-volitional verbs. Following is a chart of some common volitional and non-volitional forms.</p> <table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མགོ་སྐོར་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To deceive”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མགོ་འཁོར་ཐེབས་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To be deceived”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ཁྲོ་བསླང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To make angry”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ཁྲོ་ལང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To get angry”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡར་རྒྱས་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To improve”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡར་རྒྱས་འགྲོ་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To be improved”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མེ་མདའ་རྒྱག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To shoot”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མེ་མདའ་ཐེབས་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To be hit (by a bullet)”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མིག་ཆུ་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To shed tears”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མིག་ཆུ་ཤོར་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To burst into tears”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྟུག་དྲི་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To fart (intentionally)”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྟུག་དྲི་ཤོར་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To fart (accidentally)”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཅིན་པ་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To urinate (intentionally)</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཅིན་པ་ཤོར་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To wet oneself “</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསམ་བློ་བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To ponder”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསམ་བློ་འཁོར་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To have an idea”</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐྱུག་པ་སྐྱུག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To (make oneself) vomit”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐྱུག་པ་ཤོར་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To vomit”</p> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The honorifics of compound verbs are formed by putting both the verbalizer and the preceding noun in the honorific.</p> <table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་ས་རྒྱག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To marry”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྲུང་ས་བསྐྱོན་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To marry” (H)</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་ཀ་བྱེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To work”</p> </td> <td width=\"48\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕྱག་ལས་གནང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"414\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">“To work” (H)</p> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Compound verbs retain a certain syntactic flexibility: the noun can be separated from the verbalizer by an adverb or a negation, and may also be marked by a complement:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསམ་བློ་མང་པོ་བཏང་དགོས་རེད།</span> “(We) have to give it a lot of thought.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བུ་མོས་གཞས་སྙན་པོ་ཅིག་བཏང་སོང་།</span> “The girl sang a lovely song.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཟབ་གཟབ་མ་བྱས་ན་ཉེན་ཁ་འདུག</span> “If you’re not careful, it’s risky.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The semantics of a verb offer no clue to the verbalizer that should be used. As a general rule, compound verbs take only one verbalizer.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་ཀ་བྱེད་</span> “To work” (but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་ཀ་བཏང་</span> or *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་ཀ་རྒྱག་</span>)</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་ས་རྒྱག་</span> “To marry” (but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་ས་བྱེད་</span> or *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་ས་བཏང་</span>)</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In certain cases, however, there is a choice of which verbalizer may be used:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བེད་སྤྱོད་བཏང་</span> or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བེད་སྤྱོད་བྱེད་</span> “To use”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འགུལ་སྐྱོད་བརྒྱབ་</span> or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འགུལ་སྐྱོད་བྱེད་</span> “To move” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In some exceptional instances, different verbalizers may be used but the overall meaning is different in each case.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐད་བཏང་</span> “To call,” but <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐད་རྒྱག་</span> “To shout”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མེ་རྒྱག་</span> “To set fire,” but <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མེ་བཏང་</span> “To light,” “to make a fire”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལན་རྒྱག་</span> “To reply,” but <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལན་བཏང་</span> “To send a message”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Like all verbs, verbalizers must be followed by auxiliaries. Here is a list of the “conjugations” (in all the tense-aspects and moods) of the most common auxiliaries. Knowing all these forms will enable you to conjugate most verbs in Standard Tibetan.</p> <table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Verbalizer <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Verbalizer <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Verbalizer <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་(གཏོང་)གི་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་གི་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་གི་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་(གཏོང་)གི་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་གི་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་གི་རེད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་(གཏོང་)གི་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་གི་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་གི་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་(གཏོང་)གི་འདུག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་གི་འདུག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་ཀྱི་འདུག་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་(གཏོང་)གི་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱག་གི་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱེད་ཀྱི་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་པ་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་པ་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་པ་ཡིན་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་བྱུང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་བྱུང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་བྱུང་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་སོང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་སོང་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་སོང་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་པ་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་པ་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་པ་རེད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་ཡོད་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་བཞག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་བཞག་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་བཞག་</span></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཏང་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བརྒྱབ་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> <td width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྱས་ཡོད་རེད་</span></p> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Note: The egophoric auxiliaries and the perfect auxiliaries are not compatible with all verbs. For example, for a verb such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐད་བཏང་</span> “to call,” depending on context it is possible to use either the intentional auxiliary or the receptive auxiliary: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐད་བཏང་པ་ཡིན།</span> “I called,” <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྐད་བཏང་བྱུང་།</span> “I was called (by someone).” On the other hand, for a non-volitional verb such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་</span> “to dream,” the intentional auxiliary is incorrect *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་པ་ཡིན།</span> and instead the receptive auxiliary must be used <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་བྱུང་།</span>.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Some verbs can take a complement in the form of a direct or an indirect object, whereas others cannot. The verbalizer gives no indication as to whether a verb is “transitive” or “intransitive.” The following verbs all take an object:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོས་(རྒྱ་སྐད་)སློབ་སྦྱོང་བྱས་པ་རེད།</span> “He studied (Chinese).”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོས་(གློག་ལས་འཁྲུལ་འཁོར་)བེད་སྤྱོད་བྱས་པ་རེད།</span> “He used (the computer).”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགེ་རྒན་གྱིས་(སློབ་མ་)སྐད་བཏང་སོང་།</span> “The teacher called (the student).” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ལ་(ཁྱེད་རང་)རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་བྱུང་།</span> “I dreamed (about you).”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགེ་རྒན་གྱིས་(གནས་ཚུལ་)ངོ་སྤྲོད་ཞུས་སོང་།</span> “The teacher presented (the situation).”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་གིས་(ཆོས་)ཉམས་ལེན་ཞེ་པོ་ཅིག་བྱེད་ཀྱི་འདུག་ག</span> “He practices (the Dharma) a lot!” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Unlike the verb “to study,” the verb “to work” is not transitive, and we can’t say: *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོས་(ཤིང་)ལས་ཀ་བྱས་པ་རེད།</span> “He worked the wood.”</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><em>Note</em>: Several “intransitive” compound verbs take an ergative construction, whereas in the case of “simple” verbs this construction occurs only with transitive verbs. This may be explained by the fact that the noun that precedes the verbalizer can be assimilated to an “internal” object. In other words, the verbalizer acts as if it were an autonomous transitive verb.</p>","title":""}]}
